\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\det:\F^{n\times n}\to\F$
\end_inset

 be as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "def:AxiomsForDeterminant"
plural "false"
caps "true"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

,
 satisfying the three axioms listed there.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\F^{n\times n}$
\end_inset

 be any .
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\det$
\end_inset

 also satisfies the following properties.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If any two rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are equal,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has a zero row,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If the rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are linearly dependent,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=0.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Adding or subtracting a multiple of one row from another,
 leaves the determine unchanged.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

More generally,
 the determinant stays invariant,
 if one adds to a row,
 a linear combination of other rows (note,
 the remaining rows are left unchanged).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The determinant of a diagonal matrix or a triangular matrix is equal to the product of the diagonal entries.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Branch proof
inverted 0
status open

\begin_layout Proof
Write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\text{---} & v_{1} & \text{---}\\
 & \vdots\\
\text{---} & v_{n} & \text{---}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and proceed as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
If any two rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are equal,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}=v_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\det(A) & =\ \ \det(v_{1},\dots,\underbrace{v_{j}}_{j\text{th row}},\dots,\underbrace{v_{k}}_{k\text{th row}},\dots v_{n})\\
 & =-\det(v_{1},\dots,\underbrace{v_{k}}_{j\text{th row}},\dots,\underbrace{v_{j}}_{k\text{th row}},\dots v_{n}) & \text{By Axiom 2}\\
 & =-\det(A) & \because\text{ }v_{j}=v_{k}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and that in turn shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has a zero row,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}=(0\dots0)$
\end_inset

 is the all-zero row.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\det(A) & =\det(v_{1},\dots,v_{k},\dots v_{n})\\
 & =\det(v_{1},\dots,0\cdot v_{k},\dots v_{n}) & \because\ 0\cdot v_{k}=v_{k}\\
 & =0\cdot\det(v_{1},\dots,v_{k},\dots v_{n}) & \text{By Axiom 3}\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
If the rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are linearly dependent,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=0.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Without loss of generality,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}=\sum^{n}_{i=2}c_{i}v_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 One can therefore write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\det(A) & =\det(v_{1},v_{2},\dots v_{n})\\
 & =\det\left(\sum^{n}_{i=2}c_{i}v_{i},v_{2},\dots v_{n}\right)\\
 & =\sum^{n}_{i=2}c_{i}\cdot\det(v_{i},v_{2},\dots v_{n}) & \text{By Axiom 3}\\
 & =\sum^{n}_{i=2}c_{i}\cdot0 & \text{From Property 1}\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Adding or subtracting a multiple of one row from another,
 leaves the determine unchanged.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det(A)=\det(v_{1},\dots,v_{j},\dots v_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

Consider the determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

 which is the same as 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 except the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th row is replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}+cv_{k}$
\end_inset

,
 i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\det(A') & =\det(v_{1},\dots,\underbrace{v_{j}+cv_{k}}_{j\text{th row}},\dots v_{n})\\
 & =\det(v_{1},\dots,\underbrace{v_{j}}_{j\text{th row}},\dots v_{n})+\\
 & \quad c\det(v_{1},\dots,\underbrace{v_{k}}_{j\text{th row}},\dots v_{n}) & \text{this term is zero from Property 1}\\
 & =\det(A).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
More generally,
 the determinant stays invariant,
 if one adds to a row,
 a linear combination of other rows (note,
 the remaining rows are left unchanged).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proceeding similarly,
 one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
\text{---} & v_{1} & \text{---}\\
 & \vdots\\
\text{---} & v_{k}+\sum_{i\neq j}c_{i}v_{i} & \text{---}\\
 & \vdots\\
\text{---} & v_{n} & \text{---}
\end{array}\right| & =\det\left(v_{1},\dots,\underbrace{v_{j}+\sum_{i\neq j}c_{i}v_{i}}_{j\text{th row}},\dots v_{n}\right)\\
 & =\det\left(v_{1},\dots,\underbrace{v_{j}}_{j\text{th row}},\dots v_{n}\right)+\\
 & \quad\sum_{i\neq j}c_{i}\det\left(v_{1},\dots,\underbrace{v_{i}}_{j\text{th row}},\dots v_{n}\right) & \text{these are zero from Property 1}\\
 & =\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
\text{---} & v_{1} & \text{---}\\
 & \vdots\\
\text{---} & v_{k} & \text{---}\\
 & \vdots\\
\text{---} & v_{n} & \text{---}
\end{array}\right|\\
 & =\det(A).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
We split this into two parts
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
The determinant of a diagonal matrix is equal to the product of the diagonal entries.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
We have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left|\begin{array}{cccc}
a_{11}\\
 & a_{22}\\
 &  & \ddots\\
 &  &  & a_{nn}
\end{array}\right| & =a_{11}\left|\begin{array}{cccc}
1\\
 & a_{22}\\
 &  & \ddots\\
 &  &  & a_{nn}
\end{array}\right| & \text{Axiom 3}\\
 & =a_{11}a_{22}\left|\begin{array}{ccccc}
1\\
 & 1\\
 &  & a_{33}\\
 &  &  & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  & a_{nn}
\end{array}\right|\\
 & =a_{11}a_{22}\dots a_{nn}\left|\begin{array}{cccc}
1\\
 & 1\\
 &  & \ddots\\
 &  &  & 1
\end{array}\right|\\
 & =a_{11}a_{22}\dots a_{nn} & \text{Axiom 1.}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
The determinant of a triangular matrix is equal to the product of the diagonal entries.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is upper triangular,
 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
a_{11} & a_{12} & \cdots & a_{1n}\\
0 & a_{22} & \cdots & a_{2n}\\
\vdots &  & \ddots & \vdots\\
0 & \cdots & 0 & a_{nn}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ii}>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{1,\dots n\}$
\end_inset

.
 One can turn 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 into a diagonal matrix,
 with diagonal entries 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{11},a_{22},\dots a_{nn})$
\end_inset

 by taking linear combinations of its rows.
 For instance,
 to make 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{12}$
\end_inset

 zero,
 one can subtract from the first row 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{12}\cdot a^{-1}_{22}$
\end_inset

 times the second row 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A'=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
a_{11} & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & a_{22} & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots &  & \ddots & \vdots\\
0 & \cdots & 0 & a_{nn}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\det A & =\det A' & \text{using Property 4}\\
 & =a_{11}a_{22}\dots a_{nn} & \text{using Property 5(a) above}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ii}=0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 It is not hard to see that one can obtain,
 by a linear combination of rows,
 a matrix that 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

 such that one of its rows is zero.
 (For instance,
 suppose in a 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 matrix,
 the first and the third diagonal entries are zero.
 Then,
 it is not hard to see that the third row can be made zero,
 e.g.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\begin{array}{cccc}
0 & a_{12} & a_{13} & a_{14}\\
 & a_{22} & a_{23} & a_{24}\\
 &  & 0 & a_{34}\\
 &  &  & a_{44}
\end{array}\right|=\left|\begin{array}{cccc}
0 & 0 & a'_{13} & 0\\
 & a_{22} & a'_{23} & 0\\
 &  & 0 & 0\\
 &  &  & a_{44}
\end{array}\right|=0.
\]

\end_inset

This approach readily generalises—
look at the row corresponding to the last diagonal entry that is zero and one can make this row zero.) In this case,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\det A & =\det A' & \text{Property 4}\\
 & =0 & \text{Property 2}\\
 & =a_{11}a_{22}\cdots a_{nn} & \because\ a_{ii}=0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is lower triangular,
 one can proceed analogously.
 
