\begin_layout Subsection
Trace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Trace
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
 the trace of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tr(A)=\sum^{n}_{i=1}a_{ii}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The trace is very useful in a variety of situations.
 Here's a nice relation between determinants,
 traces and the exponentiation function,
 that is extended to matrices by its power-series
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(A):=1+x+\frac{x^{2}}{2!}+\frac{x^{3}}{3!}\cdots$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det(\exp(A))=\exp(\tr(A)).
\]

\end_inset

This also shows up in physics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Inverse
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We outline the idea behind the proof of this statement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\det A$
\end_inset

 turns out to be useful for computation of the inverse of a matrix,
 if it exists.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrices,
 since we already have the formula for inverse,
 we can try to see how it relates to the determinant,
 i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
a & b\\
c & d
\end{array}\right]^{-1} & =\frac{1}{ad-bc}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
d & -b\\
-c & a
\end{array}\right]\\
 & =\frac{1}{\det A}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
c_{11} & c_{21}\\
c_{12} & c_{22}
\end{array}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the co-factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)$
\end_inset

th entry defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{ij}=(-1)^{i+j}\det M_{ij}$
\end_inset

,
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the sub-matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 obtained by removing the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th row and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th column.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In general,
 it turns out that one can compute inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{A^{-1}=\frac{C^{T}}{\det A}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is the matrix with 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{ij}$
\end_inset

 as its entry in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th row and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th column.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Note that the equation above says 
\begin_inset Formula $(A^{-1})_{ij}=c_{ji}/\det A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Fact
\begin_inset Formula $AA^{-1}=A^{-1}A=I$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose the left and right inverses were different,
 call them 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=LI=L(AR)=(LA)R=IR=R,
\]

\end_inset

i.e.
 the left and right inverses must be the same.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:detInvert"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is invertible if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Proof sketch.
\end_layout

\end_inset

To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A\neq0$
\end_inset

 is necessary for the inverse to exist,
 suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 exists.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\det(AA^{-1}) & =\det(A)\det(A^{-1})\\
 & =\det(I)=1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

since
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Not very happy with this because we proved 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(AB)=\det A\cdot\det B$
\end_inset

 only holds when at least one of 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A,\det B$
\end_inset

 is non-zero.
 But the formula,
 it appears,
 hold in general.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(AA^{-1})=\det(I)$
\end_inset

.
 This equation can only hold if both 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A$
\end_inset

 and 
